    {
      "id": "8913fb9adacc76a1005c03f8e69ba885596085cb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 302,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "paf@cray.com",
        "username": "paf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-12-19 23:09:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nBob - There have been a number of patches put in with LU-3889 and LU-3027, which have significantly reduced the frequency of CL_LOCK issues.\n\nAre you saying, with this, that those patches were invalid/incorrect?  Also, is there a specific flaw in this patch, other than it's been observed the failures started around then?  Have any of the reproducers for those issues been tested with this and the issue-specific patches removed?\n\nI've added Oleg and Jinshan for their input on this, since they wrote some of those patches.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f3f20af11273de169d1e3b97feb256a1c749e7e4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 251,
        "name": "Bob Glossman",
        "email": "bob.glossman@intel.com",
        "username": "bogl",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-12-19 23:13:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nPatrick - I'm not saying that there is anything wrong with this patch as it appears on master associated with other related patches.  All I'm saying is that LU-3889 type failures only started appearing in b2_4 testing after this back port landed in  b2_4 and disappeared again when it was reverted.  Therefore I think the revert should land in b2_4, at least for the 2.4.2 release.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
